pe":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary hypothyroidism","Secondary hypothyroidism","Tertiary hypothyroidism","Central hypothyroidism","Mixed hypothyroidism"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe classification of hypothyroidism follows the anatomical hierarchy of the hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E results from thyroid gland dysfunction (most common cause)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecondary hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to pituitary dysfunction causing decreased thyroid stimulating hormone production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETertiary hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E results from hypothalamic dysfunction causing decreased thyrotropin-releasing hormone production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-specific term that can include both secondary and tertiary causes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard classification term\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis classification system helps clinicians identify the underlying cause and determine appropriate investigation and management strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hypothalamic causes of hypothyroidism are classified as tertiary hypothyroidism due to decreased thyrotropin-releasing hormone production","The classification of hypothyroidism follows the hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis: primary (thyroid), secondary (pituitary), tertiary (hypothalamic)"],"references":["Chaker L, Bianco AC, Jonklaas J, Peeters RP. Hypothyroidism. Lancet. 2017 Sep 23;390(10101):1550-1562. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(17)30703-1. Epub 2017 Mar 20. PMID: 28336049; PMCID: PMC6619426","Patil N, Rehman A, Anastasopoulou C, et al. Hypothyroidism. [Updated 2024 Feb 18]. In: StatPea